    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-04-03T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-04-03T12:00:00-05:00" n="176"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d176">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 European War 1939/2418: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador to the Yugoslav Government in Exile</hi>
                        (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-04-03T20:00:00+03:00"
                            >April 3, 1944—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received April 4—5:34 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Yugos 80. Instead of proceeding as stated in my Yugos 79, April 3, 5 p.m.,<note
                        n="49" xml:id="d176fn1">Not printed.</note> Lord Moyne is tonight sending
                    the following message to Marshal Antonescu from the British Government: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <list>
                            <item>“1. In your message transmitted through Theodorescu<note n="50"
                                    xml:id="d176fn2">Possibly Col. Tr. Teodorescu, Rumanian
                                    Military, Naval, and Air Attaché in Turkey.</note> you asked
                                upon what assistance from the air Rumania can count if she resists
                                the Germans. In reply we are willing to bring powerful air attack to
                                bear on such targets as you suggest.</item>
                            <item>2. You also asked whether the Allies can make some helpful
                                declaration of policy to assist you in producing will to fight among
                                Rumanians. Mr. Molotov has now made a clear declaration of which you
                                are no doubt aware.</item>
                            <pb facs="0178" n="168" xml:id="pg_168"/>
                            <item>3. You must therefore reply at once whether you accept the
                                proposals of the Soviet Government with which the other Allies are
                                fully associated.”</item>
                        </list>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
